 Task2-Domain Heirarchy
 refer to Domainheirarchy.img for clear understandng

 . = root Domain
 .com,.edu,.gov,.mil = Top level domaain(TLD)
 MIT.edu , here MIT IS Second level Domain
 NASA.gov , here NASA is second level Domain
 Google.com , here google is second level Domain
 Army.mil , here army is second level Domain

 so we have 3 domains in Heirarchy
 1) root domain
 2) top level domain
 3) second level domain

 2) TLD is further devided into two parts 
 1- gTLD = generic top level domain , like its obvious that .com is for commercial purpose and .edu is for educational purpose
 2- ccTLD = Country code top level domain , like co.uk etc
  
 3) Taking tryhackme.com as an example, the .com part is the TLD, and tryhackme is the Second Level Domain.
 When registering a domain name, the second-level domain is limited to 63 characters + the TLD and can only use a-z 0-9 and hyphens (cannot start or end with hyphens or have consecutive hyphens).

 NOW COMES SUBDOMAINS
 these are used before or leftside of second level domains
 for eg  -  admin.tryhackme.com   => here admin is SUBDOMAIN
 there is not limit of number of subdomains that can be used
 A subdomain name has the same creation restrictions as a Second-Level Domain, being limited to 63 characters and can only use a-z 0-9 and hyphens (cannot start or end with hyphens or have consecutive hyphens). You can use multiple subdomains split with periods to create longer names, such as jupiter.servers.tryhackme.com. But the length must be kept to 253 characters or less











 Task3-Record types

 DNS Record Types
 

 DNS isn't just for websites though, and multiple types of DNS record exist. We'll go over some of the most common ones that you're likely to come across.

 1) A record -: its for IPv4 addresses

 2) AAAA record -: its for IPv6 addresses

 3) CNAME record -: jaise tryhaackme ke online store ka subdomain hai store.tryhackme.com , to CNAME record ise store.shopify.com se connect ya map krega 

 4) MX record -: MX = Mail Exchange Record

Ye DNS ka record hota hai jo batata hai:

 "Is domain ki email kaha par deliver karni hai?"

Matlab agar koi tumhe mail bheje:

koi@tumhradomain.com


To MX record decide karta hai ki ye mail kaunse mail server ko milegi.

 MX Record me kya hota hai?

MX record me 2 important cheeze hoti hain:

1️- Priority

Chhota number = high priority
Agar pahla server down ho jaye, next priority wale server par mail chalegi.

2️- Mail Server Hostname

Jaise:

ASPMX.L.GOOGLE.COM
ALT1.ASPMX.L.GOOGLE.COM
mail.protonmail.ch
smtp.zoho.in

# Simple Example

Agar tum Gmail Workspace use kar rahe ho:

Priority | Mail Server
10         ASPMX.L.GOOGLE.COM
20         ALT1.ASPMX.L.GOOGLE.COM
30         ALT2.ASPMX.L.GOOGLE.COM


Iska matlab:

Pehle mail Google ke main server par jaye

Agar down ho, 2nd

Phir 3rd

4) TXT record
TXT = Text Record

Ye DNS ka ek record hota hai jisme domain owner kuch bhi text store kar sakta hai.
Mostly ye record verification aur security ke liye use hota hai.

Matlab:
 “Domain ke DNS me yeh text save kar do, jisse duniya confirm kar sake ki domain sach me tumhara hai.”
TXT Record = DNS me text store karna
Zyada tar use hota hai:

Domain verify karne ke liye

Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) ke liye









Task4- Making a request 

what happens when u make a dns request

 1. Sabse pehle Local Cache check hota hai

Tumhare computer/laptop ne agar ye domain recently open kiya ho
→ result local cache me mil jayega
→ DNS query yahi khatam.

 2. Recursive DNS Server (usually ISP ka)

Agar local cache me nahi mila:

Tera computer apne Recursive DNS Server se poochta hai (ye mostly ISP ka hota hai — Jio, Airtel, BSNL).

Yaha bhi ek cache hoti hai.

Agar waha mil gaya → direct client ko de deta.

Popular sites (Google, YouTube, Insta) ka result yahi mil jata hai.

Agar yaha bhi result nahi mila, tab actual DNS travel start hota hai.

 Ab shuru hoti hai DNS ki Journey
 3. Root DNS Servers

Recursive server sabse pehle Root Servers ko query karta hai.

Root servers ke paas domain ka exact answer nahi hota.
Unka kaam sirf yeh batana hota:

 “Is TLD (.com, .net, .in, .org) ka server yaha hai.”

Example:
“tryhackme.com” → ".com" TLD server ki taraf bhej diya jaayega.

 4. TLD (Top-Level Domain) Servers

Ab request jaati hai TLD server ke paas:

For example: .com TLD server

TLD ke paas pata hota hai ki is domain ki authoritative nameserver kaha hai.

For tryhackme.com →
It will say: authoritative DNS =

kip.ns.cloudflare.com

uma.ns.cloudflare.com

 5. Authoritative DNS Server (Nameserver)

Yahi REAL boss hota hai.

Yaha original DNS records stored hote hain
(A, MX, CNAME, TXT, etc.)

Yahi final answer deta hai:

Example:

tryhackme.com → 104.26.3.2

 6. Recursive DNS Server Result Save Karta Hai (Caching)

Record milne ke baad:

Recursive server result ko cache me store karta hai

Fir ye result tumhare computer ko bhej deta hai

Tumhara computer bhi is result ko TTL time tak store rakhta hai

TTL (Time to Live)

DNS record kitni der tak cache me store rahega —
ye TTL value (seconds) se decide hota.

Example:

TTL = 300 → 5 minutes tak record reuse hoga

TTL = 86400 → 1 day

Isse baar-baar DNS lookup karne ki zarurat nahi padti → Internet fast lagta hai.

Short Hinglish Summary

Computer → Recursive DNS → Root Server → TLD Server → Authoritative Server → Answer → Cache








